
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `echo` baraye chap kardane matn ya variable-ha rooye safhe terminal estefade mishavad.  Meslan mitavanid yek payam sade ya natijeye yek dastoor digar ra chap konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `echo -n "matn"`  --> 🤫 Jelvegiri az chap kardane khat jadid dar entehaye matn.
    🔹 `echo -e "matn\nmatn2"` --> 🗣️  Enable kardane interpretation az escape sequences mesle `\n` (khat jadid) ya `\t` (tab).
    🔹 `echo "matn > file.txt"` --> 📝 Redirect kardane output be yek file.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ echo Salam Donya!

    🔹 Chap kardane "Salam Donya!" dar terminal.

    $ echo $USER

    🔹 Chap kardane name karbari shoma.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ echo -e "Avalin khat\nKhat dovom"

    🔹 Chap kardane do khat matn ba estefade az `\n` baraye khat jadid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `echo` command is used to display text or variables on the terminal screen.  For example, you can print a simple message or the result of another command.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `echo -n "text"` --> 🤫 Prevents printing a new line at the end of the text.
    🔹 `echo -e "text\ntext2"` --> 🗣️ Enables interpretation of escape sequences like `\n` (new line) or `\t` (tab).
    🔹 `echo "text > file.txt"` --> 📝 Redirects the output to a file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ echo Hello World!

    🔹 Prints "Hello World!" to the terminal.

    $ echo $USER

    🔹 Prints your username.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ echo -e "First line\nSecond line"

    🔹 Prints two lines of text using `\n` for a new line.

